Movie Recommendation System¶

1. Project Objective¶

All entertainment websites or online stores have millions/billions of items. It becomes challenging for the customer to select the right one. At this place, recommender systems come into the picture and help the user to find the right item by minimizing the options.

Recommendation Systems in the world of machine learning have become very popular and are a huge advantage to tech giants like Netflix, Amazon and many more to target their content to a specific audience. These recommendation engines are so strong in their predictions that they can dynamically alter the state of what the user sees on their page based on the user’s interaction with the app.

2. Data Collection¶

The dataset has been obtained from Grouplens.

Link : https://grouplens.org/datasets/movielens/20m/

This dataset (ml-20m) describes 5-star rating and free-text tagging activity from MovieLens, a movie recommendation service. It contains 20000263 ratings and 465564 tag applications across 27278 movies. These data were created by 138493 users between January 09, 1995 and March 31, 2015. This dataset was generated on October 17, 2016.

Users were selected at random for inclusion. All selected users had rated at least 20 movies. No demographic information is included. Each user is represented by an id, and no other information is provided.

The data are contained in the files genome-scores.csv, genome-tags.csv, links.csv, movies.csv, ratings.csv and tags.csv.

For our objective, we would be using "ratings.csv" and "movies.csv" data files.

import pandas as pd
from datetime import datetime

# Load datasets
file_path = r"C:\Users\Hyma vathi\Desktop\Movie-Recommendation-System-main"
movie_ratings = pd.read_csv(file_path + r"\ratings.csv")
movies = pd.read_csv(file_path + r"\movies.csv")

# Ensure 'newId' exists or create it
if "newId" not in movie_ratings.columns:
    movie_ratings["newId"] = movie_ratings["movieId"]

if "newId" not in movies.columns:
    movies["newId"] = movies["movieId"]

# Convert 'timestamp' to 'date'
if "timestamp" in movie_ratings.columns:
    movie_ratings["date"] = movie_ratings["timestamp"].apply(
        lambda x: datetime.utcfromtimestamp(x).strftime("%Y-%m-%d")
    )
else:
    print("'timestamp' column not found in movie_ratings.")

# Drop 'newId'
movie_ratings.drop(["newId"], axis=1, inplace=True)
movies.drop(["newId"], axis=1, inplace=True)

# Sort by 'date'
if "date" in movie_ratings.columns:
    movie_ratings.sort_values(by="date", inplace=True)
    movie_ratings.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
else:
    print("'date' column not found in movie_ratings.")

# Display results
print(movie_ratings.head())
print(movies.head())

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Define the custom label formatter if not already defined
def changingLabels(num):
    if num >= 1e6:
        return f'{num / 1e6:.1f}M'
    elif num >= 1e3:
        return f'{num / 1e3:.1f}K'
    return str(num)

# Checking the feature "rating"
sns.set(style="darkgrid")
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(25, 5), sharey=True)

# Plot the countplot
sns.countplot(x="rating", data=movie_ratings, ax=axes)

# Set ticks and their labels explicitly
yticks = axes.get_yticks()  # Retrieve y-tick positions
axes.set_yticks(yticks)  # Explicitly set the same positions
axes.set_yticklabels([changingLabels(num) for num in yticks])  # Format the labels

# Annotate the bars with counts
for p in axes.patches:
    axes.annotate(f'{int(p.get_height())}', (p.get_x() + 0.2, p.get_height() + 100), fontsize=12)

# Adjust plot labels and title
plt.tick_params(labelsize=15)
plt.title("Distribution of Ratings in the Dataset", fontsize=20)
plt.xlabel("Ratings", fontsize=10)
plt.ylabel("Counts (in Millions)", fontsize=10)
plt.show()

Observations:

  1. The ratings given by users to movies lies in between 0.5 to 5.
  2. A high proportion of the movies have been rated 3, 3.5 or 4 by the users.
  3. The distribution of ratings look a bit left skewed as large proportion of ratings is in between 3 to 5.

# Extract unique Genres along with their count
unique_genres = {}

def ExtractGenres(x):
    for g in x.split("|"):
        if g not in unique_genres.keys():
            unique_genres[g] = 1
        else:
            unique_genres[g] = unique_genres[g] + 1

# Apply the function to the 'genres' column in the 'movies' DataFrame
movies["genres"].apply(ExtractGenres)

# Print the extracted genres count
print("Genres Extracted from the dataset.")
print(unique_genres)

import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

# Ensure 'date' column is in datetime format
Train_Data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(Train_Data['date'])

# Create a new 'DayOfWeek' column that extracts the day of the week
Train_Data['DayOfWeek'] = Train_Data['date'].dt.day_name()

# Now group by the 'DayOfWeek' and count the ratings
sns.set(style="darkgrid")
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(25, 5), sharey=True)

sns.barplot(x="DayOfWeek", y="rating", data=Train_Data.groupby(by=["DayOfWeek"], as_index=False)["rating"].count(), ax=axes)

# Add annotations on top of each bar
for p in axes.patches:
    axes.annotate('{}'.format(int(p.get_height())), (p.get_x(), p.get_height() + 100))

# Use MaxNLocator to control the number of y-axis ticks
axes.yaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(integer=True))

# Set y-axis tick labels manually, after setting the ticks

# Load Train_Data if necessary (example)
# Train_Data = pd.read_csv('train_data.csv')

# Check if 'movieId' and 'title' columns exist
if 'movieId' not in Train_Data.columns or 'title' not in Train_Data.columns:
    # If movieId or title is missing, we need to handle it
    
    # Case 1: If you have a separate movies dataset containing 'movieId' and 'title'
    try:
        # Load the movies dataset (assume it contains 'movieId' and 'title')
        movies_df = pd.read_csv('movies.csv')  # Replace with the correct file path
        Train_Data = Train_Data.merge(movies_df[['movieId', 'title']], on='movieId', how='left')
    except FileNotFoundError:
        print("Movies dataset not found. Proceeding with placeholder data.")
        
        # Case 2: If you don't have the movies dataset, generate dummy data for testing
        
        # Generate movieId if missing (creating a range of numbers)
        if 'movieId' not in Train_Data.columns:
            Train_Data['movieId'] = range(1, len(Train_Data) + 1)

        # Generate placeholder titles if missing
        if 'title' not in Train_Data.columns:
            Train_Data['title'] = ['Movie_' + str(i) for i in range(1, len(Train_Data) + 1)]

# After adding or merging movieId and title, calculate the count of ratings per movie
no_of_ratings_per_movie = Train_Data.groupby(by=["movieId", "title"], as_index=False)["rating"].count().sort_values(by=["rating"], ascending=False)

# Reset the index to clean up after grouping
no_of_ratings_per_movie = no_of_ratings_per_movie.reset_index(drop=True)

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Set the style
sns.set(style="darkgrid")

# Create subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(25, 5))
fig.suptitle("Avg Ratings per Movie", fontsize=25)

# Plotting the PDF using histplot (axes-level function)
sns.histplot(avg_ratings_per_movie["avg_rating"], kde=True, ax=axes[0], label="PDF", stat="density")
axes[0].set_title("PDF", fontsize=18)
axes[0].set_xlabel("Average Ratings by Movie", fontsize=18)
axes[0].tick_params(labelsize=15)

# Plotting the CDF using kdeplot with fill=True
sns.kdeplot(avg_ratings_per_movie["avg_rating"], cumulative=True, ax=axes[1], fill=True, label="CDF")
axes[1].set_title("CDF", fontsize=18)
axes[1].set_xlabel("Average Ratings by Movie", fontsize=18)
axes[1].tick_params(labelsize=15)

# Adjust layout
fig.subplots_adjust(wspace=2)
plt.tight_layout()

# Show plot
plt.show()

  2. The cdf shows that the avg. rating is more frequent after 3.

Conclusion :¶

Summarized Conclusions¶

1. Users and Ratings Distribution¶

  • There are over 138K unique users in the dataset. User 118205 stands out with around 9K records.
  • The majority of ratings are concentrated between 3 and 5, with most ratings being 3, 3.5, or 4. The distribution is slightly left-skewed, indicating a preference for higher ratings.
  • The mean and median ratings are approximately 3.5.

2. Movies and Genres¶

  • The dataset includes 26K+ unique movies. Notable popular movies like Pulp Fiction, Forrest Gump, Shawshank Redemption, and Silence of the Lambs have over 60K ratings each.
  • There are 19 genres, with the top genres being Drama, Comedy, Action, and Thriller. Some movies lack genre information.

3. Rating Trends Over Time¶

  • Ratings span from 1995-01-09 to 2015-03-31, with a notable spike of 91K+ ratings on 2000-11-20.
  • High activity was observed in certain months between 1996–1998 and post-2000. Activity remained steady from 2001–2010, with occasional spikes.
  • Weekdays, particularly Mondays and Tuesdays, saw more ratings compared to weekends. However, the average ratings did not vary significantly by day.

4. User Behavior Analysis¶

  • The top 10 users have rated more than 4K movies each, with user 118205 giving over 7K ratings, reflecting extreme engagement.
  • The number of ratings per user is highly right-skewed, with most users providing fewer than 1,000 ratings. The mean number of ratings per user is 142, while the median is 69.
  • User 125794 has the highest average rating of 3.81.

5. Popular Movies and Cult Classics¶

  • Cult classics from the 1990s (Pulp Fiction, Forrest Gump, Shawshank Redemption, and Silence of the Lambs) dominate in terms of ratings, each receiving over 50K ratings.
  • Among these, Shawshank Redemption holds the highest average rating of 4.56 based on over 50K ratings.

6. Insights from Distribution and Patterns¶

  • The overall distribution of ratings is skewed towards higher values, with average ratings frequently falling between 3 and 5.
  • The popularity of certain movies and active user engagement creates skewed patterns in the data.
  • Despite the variation in user activity, the overall trends suggest a steady preference for higher-rated movies.
